  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This activity is criminalized because it enables individuals or organizations to profit from illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other forms of organized crime, while also undermining the integrity of financial systems.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is addressed under various federal laws, including the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including significant fines and imprisonment. Many other countries have similar laws and participate in international efforts to combat money laundering through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. \n\nEngaging in money laundering can result in prosecution and severe legal consequences.",
